meta {
  name: POST lockunlock (NA-specific lock/unlock action endpoint)
  type: http
  seq: 7
}

post {
  url: https://b-h-s.spr.{{country}}00.p.con-veh.net/lockunlock/v1/vehicle/{{vehicle_uuid}}
  body: json
  auth: bearer
}

auth:bearer {
  token: {{access_token}}
}

body:json {
  {
    "action": "lock"
  }
}

headers {
  Accept: application/json
  Content-Type: application/json
  User-Agent: MyVW/1.0 Android
  X-Spin-Session: {{spin_session_token}}
}

docs {
  v2.10.0 (Group C). VW North America lock/unlock endpoint.

  Modern Cox firmware exposes ``/lockunlock/v1/vehicle/{uuid}`` as the
  lock/unlock action endpoint. The ``action`` body field accepts
  ``lock`` or ``unlock``. For ``unlock`` the request must carry an
  ``X-Spin-Session`` header containing the short-lived session token
  obtained via the ``/challenge`` + ``/spin`` two-step flow.

  NA-specific shape vs EU:

  - EU uses ``POST /vehicle/v1/vehicles/{vin}/access/{action}`` with
    the SPIN embedded directly in the body.
  - NA splits lock + unlock into a single dedicated endpoint and moves
    SPIN verification out-of-band via the X-Spin-Session header. This
    keeps the SPIN itself off-the-wire on the action request.

  A/B fallback contract: legacy Cox firmware (pre-2024 builds) only
  knows ``/ev/v1/vehicle/{uuid}/lock``. The Python implementation tries
  the modern endpoint first and falls back to the legacy one on a 404
  response, so existing installs keep working through the firmware
  transition window.

  ``lock`` does not require a SPIN session token; the X-Spin-Session
  header is only set on the ``unlock`` action.
}
